#Text=Find out What Time You Were Born
#Text=Not all hospitals and countries record birth times , but it might be worth the effort and fee to track down a full-length birth certificate .
#Text=The memory of your parents , midwife , or old family friends may be useful as well .
#Text=If you are trying to find the time of birth for astrological purposes , you can try to narrow an estimate using a process called star chart rectification .
#Text=Steps
#Text=Finding Your Birth Certificate or Hospital Records
#Text=Ask your parents and other people present at your birth .
#Text=Your parents might remember when you were born , or direct you to other family members or friends who were there when you were born .
#Text=They may also have a copy of your birth certificate .
#Text=If your parents have any " family history " boxed away , look through it for old diaries , family bibles , and family newsletters around the time of your birth .

column1: #Text=Know your country 's birth certificate policies .
#Text=Not all countries record the time of birth on birth certificates .
#Text=Look up the policies of the country you were born in with an online search .
#Text=In some countries , you may need to know a few more details :
#Text=In the United States , the birth time is only recorded in the " long form " birth certificate , also called the " full " version .
#Text=This information is often missing on certificates from before the 1930s , or from cities with fewer than 100,000 people .
#Text=In the United Kingdom , times of birth are only recorded for multiple births ( twins etc. ) , or in some Scottish hospitals .
#Text=Many Western European countries record birth times , but there are no official birth time records for Australia , Canada , Ireland , or India .
#Text=Request a birth certificate with birth time from the government .

#Text=If you do n't have a copy of your birth certificate , you can usually request a copy from the health department or vital records office associated with the county , province , or state where you were born .
#Text=You may need to provide multiple forms of identification , and/or pay a fee .
#Text=Always mention that you are specifically looking for a record of your birth time .
#Text=Start your quest with one of the following links , matching the country of your birth :
#Text=Australia
#Text=Canada
#Text=England or Wales , Scotland , and Northern Ireland .
#Text=The United States , or see here for more information on requirements .
#Text=Ask the hospital for records .
#Text=As a last resort , you can try checking the records department of the hospital in which you were born .
#Text=Contact the hospital through phone , email , or an in-person visit , and ask to see any records which may have the time of your birth recorded .
#Text=You may need to provide one or more forms of identification .
#Text=Estimating Your Birth Time With Astrology
#Text=Find out whether this is necessary .
#Text=If you believe that astrology can predict your future based on your birth date and time , you might have already constructed a star chart or hired someone to do so .

#Text=If your birth time is based on your mother 's memory , if it was rounded to the nearest hour on your birth certificate , or if you have no idea what it is , your star chart may be based on incorrect information .
#Text=These online calculators below will tell you how likely it is that a given type of star chart , or part of a star chart , is accurate .
#Text=Enter the number of hours you think your birth time guess could be off by , such as " 3 " if you only know the general time of day , or " 12 " if you do not know your birth time .
#Text=If there is a high chance of your star chart matching the predictions anyway , you may want to skip the arduous process below .
#Text=Moon signs for Western astrology or Vedic astrology
#Text=Zodiac sign of your ascendant
#Text=Solar arc
#Text=Dasha predictions
#Text=Have a " best guess " star chart made .
#Text=This star chart does n't have to have much detail , since it will just be a starting point .
#Text=If you do n't know your birth time at all , make the chart as though you were born at noon .
#Text=If you know it was between 4:00 and 8:30 , make the chart for 6:15 .
#Text=You can hire an astrologer if you do not know how to do this , or learn how to do it yourself .
#Text=You can also hire an astrologer to " rectify your star chart , " and skip the steps below .
#Text=Write down a list of major events .
#Text=Write down as many major events in your life that come to mind .
#Text=You 'll need a year , a date , and preferably a time for each one .
#Text=Traumatic events and accidents are the most useful , but you should also include marriage , divorce , childbirth , change of employment , and other major events .
#Text=You can use these to see whether the predictions for your current star chart match the events in your life .
#Text=Make predictions based on the star chart .
#Text=Use transits , solar arcs , and other astrology techniques to map out predictions based on the " best guess " star chart .
#Text=Here are some tips on which to use , based on how quickly the astrological bodies move through the chart .
#Text=Consult an astrology website or astrologer if you do not know how to do this :
#Text=Any solar arcs except the Ascendant , Midheaven , and Moon .
#Text=Transits for Jupiter , Saturn , Uranus , Neptune , Pluto , and the Lunar Nodes .
#Text=If you are confident of the birthday , add the Sun , Mercury , Venus , and Mars .
#Text=Compare the predictions to your actual life events .

#Text=Different astrologers use different techniques to " rectify " a star chart , but the basic idea is to see whether your life events match the predictions , or to check whether your life events can be explained by a different birth time .
#Text=Here are a few techniques experienced astrologers use :
#Text=Eliminate events that can be explained by natal planetary connections .
#Text=Look at remaining events , and see whether they are concentrated when celestial bodies arrive at specific degrees .
#Text=Those degrees could correspond to your Ascendant and Midheaven , if the positions work out .
#Text=Compare recent outer planet ( Jupiter through Pluto ) transits to recent life events , to see which house appears to influence you .
#Text=Tips
#Text=A passport will often count as multiple forms of ID , if requested , since multiple forms of ID are required to apply for one .
#Text=Warnings
#Text=Rectifying star charts is subjective , and even some people who practice astrology are not convinced it is helpful , at least if the birth time range is more than a couple hours .
#Text=Quick Summary
